POWER PURCHASE AGREEMENT BETWEEN BLACK HILLS COLORADO IPP, LLC AND BLACK HILLS/COLORADO ELECTRIC UTILITY COMPANY, LP THIS POWER PURCHASE AGREEMENT (the “PPA”) is made this 29th day of September, 2009, by and between (i) Black Hills Colorado IPP, LLC, a South Dakota limited liability company with a principal place of business at 625 Ninth Street, Rapid City, South Dakota 57709 (“Seller”), and (ii) Black Hills/Colorado Electric Utility Company, LP, a Delaware limited partnership, with offices at 625 Ninth Street, Rapid City, South Dakota 57709 (“BH/CO Electric”). Seller and BH/CO Electric are hereinafter referred to individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” WHEREAS Seller desires to plan, develop, finance, design, construct, own, operate and maintain two GE LM6000 2 x 1 combined cycle units which will be dispatchable and capable of non-intermittent operation and have a designed net power output capability during the Summer Months of 200 MW (100 MW per Unit), and which are further defined below as the “Facility”; and WHEREAS Seller intends to locate the Facility in Pueblo County, Colorado and to interconnect the Facility with BH/CO Electric’s transmission system at the 115-kV airport tap; and WHEREAS Seller desires to generate and sell to BH/CO Electric the electrical capacity and associated energy produced by the Facility and BH/CO Electric desires to buy the same from the Seller. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants herein contained, the sufficiency and adequacy of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree to the following: Article 1 - Definitions and Rules of Interpretation 1.1 Rules of Construction. The capitalized terms listed in this Article shall have the meanings set forth herein whenever the terms appear in this PPA, whether in the singular or the plural or in the present or past tense. Other terms used in this PPA but not listed in this Article shall have meanings as commonly used in the English language and, where applicable, in Good Utility Practice. Words not otherwise defined herein that have well known and generally accepted technical or trade meanings are used herein in accordance with such recognized meanings. In addition, the following rules of interpretation shall apply: (A) The masculine shall include the feminine and neuter. (B) References to "Articles," "Sections," “paragraphs” or "Exhibits" shall be to articles, sections, paragraphs or exhibits of this PPA. (C) The Exhibits attached hereto are incorporated in and are intended to be a part of this PPA; provided, in the event of a conflict between the terms of any Exhibit and the terms of this PPA, the terms of this PPA shall take precedence. (D) This PPA was negotiated and prepared by both Parties with the advice and participation of counsel. The Parties have agreed to the wording of this PPA and none of the provisions hereof shall be construed against one Party on the ground that such Party is the author of this PPA or any part hereof. (E) The Parties shall act reasonably and in accordance with the principles of good faith and fair dealing in the performance of this PPA. Unless expressly provided otherwise in this PPA, (a) where the PPA requires the consent, approval, or similar action by a Party, such consent or approval shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed, and (b) wherever the PPA gives a Party a right to determine, require, specify or take similar action with respect to a matter, such determination, requirement, specification or similar action shall be reasonable. (F) Use of the words “include” or “including” or similar words shall be interpreted as “include but not limited to” or “including, without limitation.” (G) Use of the words “tax” or “taxes” shall be interpreted to include taxes, fees, surcharges, and the like. 1.2 Interpretation with Interconnection Agreement. Each Party conducts its operations in a manner intended to comply with FERC Order No. 2004, Standards of Conduct for Transmission Providers, requiring the separation of its transmission and merchant functions. Moreover, the Parties acknowledge that BH/CO Electric’s transmission function offers interconnection and transmission service on its system in a manner intended to comply with FERC policies and requirements relating to the provision of open-access transmission service. The Parties recognize that Seller will enter into a separate LGIA with the Interconnection Provider for each Unit. (A) The Parties acknowledge and agree that the LGIAs shall be separate and free-standing contracts, and that the terms of this PPA are not binding upon the Interconnection Provider. (B) Notwithstanding any other provision in this PPA, nothing in the LGIAs shall alter or modify Seller’s or BH/CO Electric’s rights, duties and obligations under this PPA. This PPA shall not be construed to create any rights between Seller and the Interconnection Provider. (C) Seller expressly recognizes that, for the purposes of this PPA, the Interconnection Provider shall be deemed to be a separate entity and separate contracting party whether or not the LGIAs are entered into with BH/CO Electric, an Affiliate of BH/CO Electric, or a party unaffiliated with BH/CO Electric. 1.3 Interpretation with Arrangements for Electric Supply to the Facility. This PPA does not provide for the supply of retail power to the Facility, for purposes of Facility start-up or shut-down, or for any other purpose (“House Power”). Seller shall contract with the local utility in whose retail service territory the Facility is located (“Local Provider”) for the supply of House Power. (A) Seller’s arrangements for the supply of House Power to the Facility shall be separate and free-standing arrangements. The terms of this PPA are not binding upon the Local Provider. For purposes of this PPA, the Local Provider shall be deemed to be a separate entity and separate contracting party, whether or not the Local Provider is BH/CO Electric, an Affiliate of BH/CO Electric, or a party unaffiliated with BH/CO Electric. (B) Notwithstanding any other provision in this PPA, nothing in Seller’s arrangements for the supply of House Power to the Facility shall alter or modify Seller's or BH/CO Electric's rights, duties and obligations under this PPA. This PPA shall not be construed to create any rights between Seller and the Local Provider. (C) Subject to Seller’s right to self-generate and consume energy concurrently generated by the Facility, Seller shall obtain House Power exclusively from the Local Provider. Seller shall not obtain House Power back through the Interconnection Facilities, and waives any regulatory or other legal right to the contrary. 1.4 Definitions. The following terms shall have the meanings set forth herein: “Abandonment” means (i) the relinquishment of all possession and control of the Facility by Seller, other than a transfer permitted under this PPA, or (ii) if prior to the Commercial Operation Date, complete cessation of design, construction, testing and inspection of the Facility for thirty (30) consecutive Days by Seller or Seller’s contractors, but only if such relinquishment or cessation is not caused by or attributable to an Event of Default of, or request by, BH/CO Electric, or an event of Force Majeure. “Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel” means natural gas fuel that meets the Facility manufacturer’s fuel specifications and the Facility’s permit requirements, is available to the Facility during the term of this PPA, under delivery arrangements that meet the requirements of Section 5.5 of this PPA, and is not contrary to Good Utility Practice. “Actual Net Heat Rate” means the net heat rate for the Facility, stated in Btu/kWh, Higher Heating Value (“HHV”), as adjusted to Reference Conditions, resulting from a heat rate test conducted in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth in Section 8.5, which shall be used for determining the Heat Rate Adjustment to payments as specified in Sections 8.3 and 8.4. “Affiliate” of any named entity means any person or other entity that controls, is under the control of, or is under common control with, the named entity. The term “control” (including the terms “controls”, “under the control of” and “under common control with”) means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management of the policies of an entity, whether through ownership interest, by contract or otherwise. "Air Permit" means the air permit issued or to be issued by Colorado Department of Health and Environment required for Seller to construct, if applicable, and operate the Facility and to generate Contract Capacity and Contract Energy for purposes of this PPA. "Applicable Law" means all applicable laws, statutes, treaties, codes, ordinances, regulations, certificates, orders, licenses and permits of any Governmental Authority, now in effect or hereafter enacted, amendments to any of the foregoing, interpretations of any of the foregoing by a Governmental Authority having jurisdiction, and all applicable judicial, administrative, arbitration and regulatory decrees, judgments, injunctions, writs, orders, awards or like actions of a Governmental Authority (including those relating to human health, safety, the natural environment or otherwise). “Automatic Generation Control,” or “AGC,” means the automatic regulation within predetermined limits of the power output of electric generators within a Control Area in response to changes in system load, system frequency, tie line load, or the relation of these to each other, so as to maintain the scheduled system frequency or the established interchange with other Control Areas. This regulation is accomplished through communication links between the GDPM energy management system and each generator equipped for such control. For a generator to be considered capable of AGC by BH/CO Electric, the generator must meet the Requirements and Compliance Standards for Dispatchability. "Availability Verification Test" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 5.2(A). “Avoided Cost Rate” shall mean BH/CO Electric’s then-current tariff rate reflecting the avoided cost of energy applicable to co-generation and small power producers ranging from less than one (1) kilowatt up to one hundred (100) kilowatts (currently, as of the date of this PPA, $.03801 per Kilowatt-hour), or, if such tariff rate no longer exists, a rate agreed upon by the Parties that approximates the cost to BH/CO Electric of energy displaced by Test Energy pursuant to Section 4.9 of this PPA, “Balance of Plant Contracts” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 4.4(A). "BH/CO Electric" shall mean Black Hills/Colorado Electric Utility Company, LP, a Delaware limited partnership. "Btu" means British thermal unit. “Business Day” means any Day that is not a Saturday, a Sunday, or a NERC recognized holiday. "CAF" stands for Capacity Availability Factor and shall have the meaning set forth in Section 8.1. "Capital Improvement" means any addition, betterment, enlargement, replacement or other change to or of any component, equipment or system from time to time affixed to, installed on, incorporated into, added to or constituting part of the Facility, or to constitute part of the Facility as the result of any permit condition for the Facility during the Term hereof, the cost of which is or should be capitalized in accordance with Good Utility Practices and Applicable Law and not charged to maintenance or repairs in accordance with Good Utility Practices and Applicable Law. “Changed Standards” means any changes subsequent to the date of this PPA by any Governmental Authority or entity that sets standards of general applicability to generation facilities similar in size and operating characteristics to the Units or Facility. “Commercial Operation” means the period beginning on the Commercial Operation Date and continuing through the Term of this PPA. “Commercial Operation Date” or “COD” means, subject to verification by BH/CO Electric pursuant to Section 4.8, the date on which Seller notifies BH/CO Electric, pursuant to Section 4.8, that all of the Conditions have occurred or otherwise been satisfied. “Commercial Operation Milestone” means the Construction Milestone for the Commercial Operation Date. The Commercial Operation Milestone is January 1, 2012, unless extended pursuant to paragraph 4.1(B) of this PPA. “Commercial Operation Year” means each calendar year or partial calendar year during the period of Commercial Operation. “Conditions” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 4.8. “Construction Contract(s)” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 4.4(A). “Construction Milestones” means the dates set forth in Exhibit B by which Seller is scheduled to achieve the corresponding results specified for such dates, including the Commercial Operation Milestone. “Contract Capacity” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 7.1(A). “Contract Energy” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 7.1(B). “Contracts” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 4.4(A). “Control Area” means the collection of generation, distribution, and transmission facilities and loads within which generation is regulated in order to maintain interchange schedules with other such systems. “CPUC” means the Colorado Public Utilities Commission or any successor agency. “CPUC Approval” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 6.1(A). “Day” means a calendar day. "Deficiency" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 5.2(A). "Delay Damages" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 12.4(A). "Dispatch Availability Factor" shall have the meaning set forth in Section 8.2. "Dispatchability Payment" shall have the meaning set forth in Section 8.2. "Dispute" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 13.9(A). "Dispute Notice" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 13.9(A). “Electric Metering Devices” means all Interconnection Provider owned meters, metering equipment, and data processing equipment used to measure, record, or transmit data relating to the electric power and energy output from the Facility. Electric Metering Devices include the metering current transformers (“CTs”) and the metering voltage transformers (“VTs”). “Elevated System Condition” means any period of time during the Term in which GDPM, BH/CO Electric’s transmission function, or any governing authority responsible for reliability of the bulk electric system declares an elevated concern regarding system reliability. “Emergency” means any emergency condition (as defined in the LGIAs), or any abnormal interconnection or other system condition, that requires automatic or immediate manual action to prevent or limit loss of BH/CO Electric’s load or generation supply, that could adversely affect the reliability of the regional electric system or generation supply, that could adversely affect the reliability of any interconnected system or in the western interconnection, or that could otherwise pose a threat to public safety. "Encumbrances" means any mortgage, pledge, lien, encumbrance, security interest easement, lease, financing statement or other adverse right encumbering the title of real or personal property, except for Permitted Encumbrances. “Environmental Contamination” means the introduction or presence of Hazardous Materials at such levels, quantities or location, or of such form or character, as to constitute a violation of Applicable Law, and to present a material risk under Applicable Law that the Site will not be available or usable for the purposes contemplated by this PPA. “EPC Contract” indebtedness, fees, expenses or penalties, amounts due upon acceleration, prepayment or restructuring, swap or interest rate hedging breakage costs and any claims or interest due with respect to any of the foregoing. “Facility Lender” means, collectively, any lenders providing any Facility Debt and any successors or assigns thereto. "Federal Power Act" means the provisions of 16 U.S.C. 791a et seq. and amendments or supplements thereto. “FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor agency. “Financing Documents” means the loan and credit agreements, notes, bonds, indentures, security agreements, lease financing agreements, mortgages, deeds of trust, interest rate exchanges, swap agreements and other documents relating to the debt financing of the Seller or any of its Affiliates (other than BH/CO Electric), as applicable, including any credit enhancement, credit support, working capital financing, or refinancing documents, and any and all amendments, modifications, or supplements to the foregoing that may be entered into from time to time at the discretion of Seller. “Force Majeure” shall have the meaning set forth in Article 14. “Forced Outage” means any condition at the Facility that requires immediate removal of the Facility, or some part thereof, from service, another outage state, or a reserve shutdown state. This type of outage results from immediate mechanical/electrical/hydraulic control system trips and operator-initiated trips in response to Facility conditions and/or alarms. “Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum” shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 5.5(C). "Generation Benefits" means all environmental credits, offsets, allowances or benefits that are attributable to electric energy generated by the Facility and delivered to BH/CO Electric during the Term, including air emissions credits and emissions reductions credits, offsets, allowances or benefits whether promulgated by a Governmental Authority or by or through any other means. Generation Benefits includes not only the described credits, offsets, allowances or benefits that are now available, but also the described credits, offsets, allowances or benefits that may become available in the future for electric energy generated by the Facility during the Term. "Generation Dispatch and Power Marketing," or "GDPM," means BH/CO Electric's merchant representatives responsible for dispatch of generating units, including the Facility. “Good Utility Practice(s)” means the practices, methods, and acts (including the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the fuel supply and electric power generation industry, in the WECC and/or NERC) that, at a particular time, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known or that should reasonably have been known at the time a decision was made, would have been expected to accomplish the desired result in a manner consistent with law, regulation, permits, codes, standards, equipment manufacturer’s recommendations, reliability, safety, environmental protection, economy, and expedition. Good Utility Practice(s) are not intended to be limited to the optimum practices, methods or acts, to the exclusion of all others, but rather to include a spectrum of possible practices, methods or acts generally acceptable in the region during the relevant period in light of the circumstances. With respect to the Facility, the desired result of the Good Utility Practice(s) is that: (A) equipment, materials, resources, and supplies, including water and fuel supply and spare parts inventories, are available to meet the Facility’s needs; (B) sufficient operating personnel are available at all times and are adequately experienced and trained and licensed as necessary to operate the Facility properly, efficiently, and in coordination with BH/CO Electric and are capable of responding to reasonably foreseeable Emergency conditions whether caused by events on or off the Site; (C) preventive, routine, and non routine maintenance and repairs are performed on a basis that ensures reliable, long term and safe operation, and are performed by knowledgeable, trained, and experienced personnel utilizing proper equipment and tools; (D) appropriate monitoring and testing are performed to ensure equipment comprising the Facility is functioning as designed; (E) equipment is not operated in a reckless manner, in violation of manufacturer’s guidelines or in a manner unsafe to workers, the general public, or the interconnected system or contrary to environmental laws, permits or regulations or without regard to defined limitations such as steam pressure, temperature, and moisture content, chemical content of make up water, flood conditions, safety inspection requirements, operating voltage, current, volt ampere reactive (VAr) loading, frequency, rotational speed, polarity, synchronization, or control system limits; (F) equipment and components meet or exceed the standard of durability that is generally used for gas-fired electric generation operations in the region and will function properly over the full range of ambient temperature and weather conditions reasonably expected to occur at the Site and under both normal and Emergency conditions; and (G) equipment, components, and processes are appropriately permitted with any local, state, or federal Governmental Authority and are operated and maintained in accordance with applicable permit and regulatory requirements. “Governmental Authority” means any federal, state, local, tribal, or municipal governmental body; any governmental, quasi-governmental, regulatory or administrative agency, commission, body or other authority exercising or entitled to exercise any administrative, executive, judicial, legislative, policy, regulatory or taxing authority or power; or any court or governmental tribunal having jurisdiction over a subject matter of this PPA. The term “Governmental Authority” also means, where applicable, any balancing authority to which BH/CO Electric is subject by Applicable Law or contract and NERC, WECC or other organizations to which BH/CO Electric is subject by Applicable Law or contract. “Governmental Imposition” means any change to capital expenditures or other costs incurred by Seller in connection with performing its obligations under this PPA and resulting from new statutes, ordinances, regulations, rules, taxes, fees, or other governmental mandates enacted, promulgated, or otherwise made effective by any Governmental Authority after the date hereof, or from any amendment, modification, or change after the date hereof to the text, interpretation, or application of any existing statute, ordinance, regulation, rule, tax, fee, or other governmental mandate; provided, however, that Governmental Impositions shall not include changes to income taxes or property taxes, or inflationary adjustments to taxes or fees that are not otherwise Governmental Impositions. “Governmental Imposition Charge” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 8.8. “Hazardous Materials” means any substance, material, gas, or particulate matter that is regulated by any Governmental Authority as an environmental pollutant or dangerous to public health, public welfare, or the natural environment including, without limitation, protection of non-human forms of life, land, water, groundwater, and air, including any material or substance that is (i) defined as “toxic,” “polluting,” “hazardous waste,” “hazardous material,” “hazardous substance,” “extremely hazardous waste,” “solid waste” or “restricted hazardous waste” under any provision of Applicable Law; (ii) petroleum, including any fraction, derivative or additive; (iii) asbestos; (iv) polychlorinated biphenyls; (v) radioactive material; (vi) designated as a “hazardous substance” pursuant to the Clean Water Act, 33 U.S.C. §1251 et seq. "Heat Rate Adjustment" shall have the meaning set forth in Section 8.4. “House Power” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 1.3. “Interconnection Facilities” means Interconnection Provider’s Interconnection Facilities and Seller’s Interconnection Facilities. "Interconnection Provider" means the BH/CO Electric transmission function or the person or entity that owns and operates, pursuant to the OATT, the transmission lines, Interconnection Provider's Interconnection Facilities and other equipment and facilities with which the Facility interconnects at the Point of Delivery, and any successors or assigns thereto. “Interconnection Provider’s Interconnection Facilities” means the facilities necessary to connect Interconnection Provider’s existing electric system to the Point of Delivery, including breakers, bus work, bus relays, and associated equipment installed by the Interconnection Provider for the direct purpose of interconnecting the Facility, along with any easements, rights of way, surface use agreements and other interests or rights in real estate reasonably necessary for the construction, operation and maintenance of such facilities. Arrangements for the installation and operation of the Interconnection Provider’s Interconnection Facilities shall be governed by the LGIAs. “Interconnection Provider’s System” means the contiguously interconnected electric transmission and sub-transmission facilities, including Interconnection Provider’s Interconnection Facilities, over which the Interconnection Provider has rights (by ownership or contract) to provide bulk transmission of capacity and energy from the Point of Delivery pursuant to the OATT. "Issuer" shall have the meaning set forth in paragraph 11.1(C). "kW" means kilowatt. "kWh" means kilowatt hour. “Lender Consent” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 19.2. "LGIA” means the separate large generator interconnection agreement between Seller and the Interconnection Provider for interconnection of the Facility to the Interconnection Provider's System pursuant to the OATT, as such agreement may be amended from time to time. For clarity, there will be one LGIA for each Unit. "MW" means megawatt or one thousand kW. "MWh" means megawatt hour. "Maintenance Schedule" has the meaning set forth in Section 10.1. Article 3 - Facility Description 3.1 Summary Description. Seller shall design, construct, own, operate, and maintain the Facility, which shall be a natural gas-fueled, combined cycle electric generation facility consisting of two GE LM6000 2 x 1 combined cycle units having a designed net power output capability during the Summer Months of 200 MW (100 MW per Unit). Exhibit C to this PPA, which is attached hereto and made a part hereof, provides a description of the Facility, including the following: (A) identification of the equipment and components that make up the Facility; and (B) the Minimum Loading levels expected to be available for dispatch by BH/CO Electric, with AGC and without AGC, for each possible operating configuration of the Facility generating unit(s). 3.2 Location. The Facility shall be located on the Interconnection Provider’s System on the Site and shall be identified as Seller’s Airport Power Project. A scaled map that identifies the Site, the location of the Facility at the Site, the location of the Point of Delivery, and the location of the important fuel delivery and electric facilities associated with the Site is included in Exhibit C to this PPA. 3.3 General Design of the Facility. Seller shall construct the Facility according to Good Utility Practice(s) and the LGIAs. During Commercial Operation, Seller shall maintain the Facility according to Good Utility Practice(s) and the LGIAs. In addition to the requirements of the LGIAs, the Facility shall be designed to: (A) have the required panel space and 125vDC battery supplied voltage to accommodate BH/CO Electric’s metering, generator telemetering equipment and communications equipment; (B) use communication circuits from the Facility capable of communicating Facility operating information to BH/CO Electric’s GDPM on a real-time basis for the purpose of telemetering, supervisory control/data acquisition, and voice communications as required for AGC; (C) be capable of transmitting Facility operating information to BH/CO Electric’s GDPM on a real-time basis (D) be capable of AGC by BH/CO Electric, by separate signal, for each individual generating unit and, if applicable, that portion of the Facility operated in combined-cycle mode; (E) be capable of starting and fully operating all Facility combustion turbine generating units; (F) be capable of operating at, and making available for dispatch by BH/CO Electric, the Minimum Loading levels specified in Exhibit C for operations with AGC and without AGC for each possible operating configuration of the Facility generating unit(s); (G) be capable of starting all Facility combustion turbine generating units, synchronizing all such units to the Interconnection Provider’s System and having all such units generating at their Minimum Loading levels, as specified in Exhibit C, within one hundred twenty (120) minutes of receiving the turbine start dispatch request from BH/CO Electric’s GDPM; (H) be capable of operating, or continuing to operate without interruption, all Facility combustion turbine generating units in simple-cycle mode in the event of a planned or unplanned outage of the steam turbine generating unit(s); and (I) be capable of operating, or continuing to operate without interruption, in combined-cycle mode in the event of a planned or unplanned outage of one or more, but not all, Facility combustion turbine generating unit(s). 3.4 Net Capability. The Net Capability is 200,000 kW. Article 4 - Commercial Operation 4.1 Commercial Operation. (A) Subject to the provisions of paragraph (B) below and to the extension provisions of paragraph 12.(C), the Facility shall achieve the Commercial Operation Date, and shall be fully capable of reliably producing the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy to be provided under this PPA and delivering such power and energy to BH/CO Electric at the Point of Delivery, as determined pursuant to Section 4.8 of this PPA, no later than the Commercial Operation Milestone; provided, that Seller shall not be obligated to establish a Commercial Operation Date under this PPA that is earlier than the Commercial Operation Milestone and BH/CO Electric shall not be obligated to establish a Commercial Operation Date under this PPA that is earlier than the Commercial Operation Milestone. (B) In the event the requirements of paragraph (A) above are not met by the Commercial Operation Milestone, Seller shall have the option to provide Seller’s Replacement Power until such time as all of the Conditions of Section 4.8 have occurred or otherwise been satisfied and BH/CO Electric has verified the same. If Seller exercises such option, then the Commercial Operation Milestone shall be extended to July 1, 2012 or such earlier date, on or after January 1, 2012, when Seller fails to provide Seller’s Replacement Power (unless excused by Force Majeure). Such option shall be exercised by written notice delivered to BH/CO Electric no later than July 1, 2011. (C) In the event at any time prior to the Commercial Operation Milestone, as the same may be extended pursuant to paragraph (B) above, only a portion of the Facility has met the requirements of paragraph (A) above, BH/CO Electric may, upon mutual agreement with Seller, declare a “Partial Completion Declaration” that the requirements of the Commercial Operation Date have been achieved with respect to that portion of the Facility. From and after the date of a Partial Completion Declaration, all of the rights and duties of the Parties shall continue including payments for capacity and energy under Article 8, which shall be prorated for the portion of the Facility included in the Partial Completion Declaration, the dispatch and maintenance requirements of this PPA, and the Seller’s Replacement Power or delay damages provisions, if applicable, prorated for the portion of the Facility not included in the Partial Completion Declaration. 4.2 Construction Milestones. In order to achieve the Commercial Operation Date by the Commercial Operation Milestone, Seller agrees to use commercially reasonable efforts to meet the Construction Milestones set forth in Exhibit B to this PPA. 4.3 Site Report. Seller shall conduct a Phase I environmental investigation of the Site and shall provide BH/CO Electric, within sixty (60) Days following satisfaction (or waiver, if applicable) of all conditions precedent set forth in Article 6, with a copy of the report summarizing such investigation, together with any data or information generated pursuant to such investigation. Seller shall provide to BH/CO Electric, with such report, confirmation from an environmental engineer that the Site has been inspected for Environmental Contamination and that the Site complies in all material respects with all Applicable Laws relating to environmental or occupational health and safety matters and Hazardous Materials. The term Applicable Laws in this Section shall specifically also include all statutes identified in Section 1.4 under the definition of "Hazardous Materials" and all federal, state, tribal and local environmental health and safety statutes, ordinances, codes, rules, regulations, orders and decrees regulating, relating to, or imposing liability or standards concerning or in connection with Hazardous Materials. Such report, or other written confirmation provided by Seller, shall include a confirmation that based upon such investigation and to the best of Seller's knowledge; no conditions involving Environmental Contamination exist at or under the Site. 4.4 Facility Contracts and Permit Application. Information that is commercially sensitive, confidential or proprietary (including pricing information) may be redacted from the Contracts, drafts of Contracts, and other documents provided to BH/CO Electric under this PPA (whether under this paragraph 4.4(B) or otherwise), provided that Seller must provide unredacted versions of such documents at such time that Seller is required to transfer such documents to BH/CO Electric pursuant to this PPA. If requested, Seller shall provide sufficient written information for BH/CO Electric to be reasonably assured that the contractors under the Contracts have contracted with financially responsible vendors under their Contracts. 4.5 Progress Reports. Seller shall submit to BH/CO Electric, on the fifth Day of each calendar month until the Commercial Operation Date is achieved, progress reports in a form reasonably satisfactory to BH/CO Electric. These progress reports shall notify BH/CO Electric of the current status of each Construction Milestone. Seller shall also (i) hold monthly engineering and construction progress meetings once Facility engineering commences to review and discuss such progress reports; and (ii) make the necessary contractors available in person or by telephone to discuss and answer reasonable questions of BH/CO Electric regarding the Facility and Construction Milestone progress in order to keep BH/CO Electric fully informed on the status of engineering, procurement and construction for the Facility and (iii) consider BH/CO Electric's comments in good faith. 4.6 BH/CO Electric's Rights During Construction. BH/CO Electric shall have the right to monitor the construction, start up, permitting procedures, negotiations with major equipment dealers and testing of the Facility, and Seller shall comply with all reasonable requests of BH/CO Electric with respect to the monitoring of these events. Seller shall cooperate in such physical inspections of the Facility as may be reasonably requested by BH/CO Electric during and after completion of construction. All persons visiting the Facility on behalf of BH/CO Electric shall comply with Applicable Laws and all of Seller's applicable safety and health rules and requirements. BH/CO Electric's technical review and inspection of the Facility shall not be construed as endorsing the design thereof or as any warranty of safety, durability or reliability of the Facility. 4.7 Permits. Seller shall use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain, and shall pay for, all applicable environmental and other permits, licenses and approvals from any Governmental Authority required under Applicable Law for construction, ownership, operation and maintenance of the Facility (“Applicable Permits”). BH/CO Electric shall have the right to inspect and obtain copies of all Applicable Permits held by Seller. Seller will notify BH/CO Electric of any known inspections by any Governmental Authority relating to any Applicable Permit. 4.8 Conditions to Commercial Operation. Seller shall notify BH/CO Electric in writing when the Facility has achieved the Commercial Operation Date. This notification is contingent upon verification by BH/CO Electric, including Seller providing evidence reasonably acceptable to BH/CO Electric of the satisfaction or occurrence of all of the conditions set forth in this Section (“Conditions”). The Parties agree that review and approval of such Conditions may occur on an ongoing and incremental basis, pending resolution of any dispute, as such Conditions are satisfied. The Conditions are: (A) Seller has successfully completed that testing of the Facility that is required by the Financing Documents, the Facility’s governmental permits, the LGIAs, Seller’s operating agreements, Seller’s Contracts, and manufacturers’ warranties for the commencement of commercial operations at the Facility; (B) the Facility has (i) achieved three (3) successful starts of each of its combustion turbines in simple-cycle operation without experiencing any abnormal operating conditions, (ii) achieved one (1) successful start of the combustion turbines and the steam turbine of each Unit, in combined-cycle operation, without experiencing any abnormal operating conditions, (iii) generated in each possible combined-cycle operating configuration while synchronized to Interconnection Provider’s System at full capacity without experiencing any abnormal operating conditions, and (iv) generated continuously for a period of not less than sixteen (16) hours while synchronized to Interconnection Provider’s System at a net capacity output of at least ninety percent (90%) of the Net Capability without experiencing any abnormal operating conditions; (C) an independent professional engineer’s certification has been obtained by Seller stating that the Facility has been completed in all material respects (excepting punch list items that do not materially and adversely affect the ability of the Facility to operate as intended hereunder) in accordance with this PPA and, subject to the Operating Standards, may lawfully be operated as contemplated by this PPA in compliance with all Applicable Laws; (H) staffing and training of personnel for the operation, maintenance and asset management of the Facility has been completed; (I) certificates of insurance evidencing the coverages required by Article 16 have been obtained and submitted to BH/CO Electric; (J) Seller has developed a written cold weather policy suitable for the Facility, reasonably acceptable to BH/CO Electric, to comply with the Operating Standards under Section 10.2, and provided a copy to BH/CO Electric; Article 5 - Delivery, Availability Reporting, Metering and Fuel Supply 5.1 Delivery Arrangements. (A) Seller shall be responsible for making, maintaining and paying the costs associated with an interconnection request with Interconnection Provider for interconnecting the Facility to the Interconnection Provider's system. Seller shall be responsible for entering into an LGIA with the Interconnection Provider for each Unit. Each LGIA shall state that the Unit is receiving Network Resource Interconnection Service (as that term is defined in the LGIA). Network Resource Interconnection Service shall allow the Facility to be a Network Resource of BH/CO Electric and permit delivery and transformation of the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy on Seller's side of the Point of Delivery. The Point of Delivery shall be the Airport Switchyard within the BH/CO Electric Control Area and subject to the OATT during the Term. (B) In the event Seller is unable, despite reasonable efforts, to enter into LGIAs for the Units to receive Network Resource Interconnection Service and the LGIAs instead require Seller to utilize Energy Resource Interconnection Service (as that term is defined in the LGIA), BH/CO Electric shall be responsible for seeking to designate the Facility as a Network Resource under the OATT. The Parties will cooperate reasonably and undertake any reasonably necessary responsibilities to have the Facility designated as a Network Resource. Furthermore, should an alternate market design be implemented that materially changes the interconnection and delivery requirements in this PPA, the Parties will cooperate reasonably and undertake any reasonably necessary responsibilities to mitigate the impact to the Parties under this PPA. (C) Seller shall provide the Interconnection Provider and any applicable transmission owners written permission to release interconnection and transmission-related study results to BH/CO Electric, and to discuss those results with BH/CO Electric. (D) Seller shall be responsible for all interconnection, electric losses, transmission and ancillary service arrangements and costs required to deliver, on a firm transmission service basis, the Contract Capacity, Contract Energy and Test Energy from the Facility to BH/CO Electric at the Point of Delivery as a Network Resource for the Term. (E) BH/CO Electric shall be responsible for all electric losses, transmission and ancillary service arrangements and costs required to receive the Contract Capacity, Contract Energy and Test Energy from the Point of Delivery to points beyond the Point of Delivery. 5.2 Availability Reporting. (A) Seller shall be responsible for providing accurate and timely updates on the current availability of the Contract Capacity for each Unit to BH/CO Electric’s GDPM (“Reported Availability”). BH/CO Electric shall have the right to verify at any time, without prior notice to Seller, Seller’s current Reported Availability. To verify Seller’s Reported Availability, BH/CO Electric shall dispatch the Contract Capacity of each Unit to the level of Reported Availability (“Availability Verification Test”). If the tested availability (rounded upward to the next whole MW) is less than ninety-five percent (95%) of the Reported Availability (rounded upward to the next whole MW), the results of the test shall be identified as a “Deficiency”. In the event of a Deficiency, the Contract Capacity availability shall be derated to the level in MW of the tested available capacity for the then current hour and all subsequent hours until Seller reports a revised level of available Contract Capacity. Upon receiving notice from Seller of a revised Reported Availability, BH/CO Electric shall have the option of conducting a second Availability Verification Test. If BH/CO Electric chooses not to conduct a second Availability Verification Test at that time, the Contract Capacity will be considered available to the full level of Seller’s Reported Availability until BH/CO Electric conducts a subsequent Availability Verification Test. The resulting amount of Contract Capacity available for any individual hour shall be integrated over the hour, on a prorated basis, to reflect any updates in Seller’s Reported Availability made effective during such hour. (B) BH/CO Electric will notify Seller as soon as possible by telephone and thereafter in writing whenever an Availability Verification Test has identified a Deficiency from Seller’s Reported Availability. A second and any subsequent Deficiencies to any one Unit in any billing month shall result in a retroactive derating of the Contract Capacity availability to the capacity level in MW achieved in the most recent Availability Verification Test. The period for retroactive adjustment will be all prior hours in which Seller’s most recent Reported Availability was continuously in effect and unverified by BH/CO Electric. For example, if for the first hour of the first day of a billing month the Reported Availability was 100 MW at the time of an Availability Verification Test and the tested availability was 85 MW, the results of the test would constitute a Deficiency and the Contract Capacity availability would be derated to 85 MW for the then current hour and all subsequent hours until Seller reports a revised level of available Contract Capacity. If, in the same billing month for the first hour of the second day, Seller subsequently reports a Reported Availability of 100 MW and BH/CO Electric chooses not to conduct a second Availability Verification Test at that time, the Contract Capacity will be considered available to the full level of Seller’s Reported Availability (100 MW) until BH/CO Electric conducts a subsequent Availability Verification Test. However, if BH/CO Electric conducts a subsequent Availability Verification Test on the fifth day of the billing month and the tested availability is 92 MW, the results of the test would constitute a second Deficiency and would result in a retroactive derating of the Contract Capacity availability to 92 MW retroactive to the first hour of the second day of the billing month for which Seller reported an availability of 100 MW which was at that time, unverified. In no event will the period for retroactive availability adjustments exceed ten (10) Days or extend beyond the first Day of the billing month. Three (3) Deficiencies in any two (2) consecutive billing months shall result in a five percent (5%) reduction in the Capacity Price, as set forth in Section 8.1, applicable to the subsequent two billing months. 5.3 Electric Metering Devices. (A) All Electric Metering Devices used to measure the net capacity and energy made available to BH/CO Electric by Seller under this PPA at the Point of Delivery and to monitor and coordinate operation of the Facility shall be owned, installed, and maintained in accordance with the LGIAs at no cost to BH/CO Electric under this PPA. If Electric Metering Devices are not installed at the Point of Delivery, meters or meter readings will be adjusted to reflect losses from the Electric Metering Devices to the Point of Delivery. Seller shall provide BH/CO Electric access to all Electric Metering Devices for all purposes necessary to perform under this PPA and shall provide BH/CO Electric the opportunity to be present at any time such Electric Metering Devices are to be inspected and tested or adjusted in accordance with this Article 5, subject to any required consent or other agreement from the Interconnection Provider, which Seller shall use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain. (B) Either BH/CO Electric or Seller may elect to install and maintain, at its own expense, backup metering devices (“Back-Up Metering”) in addition to those installed and maintained pursuant to the LGIAs, which installation and maintenance shall be performed in a manner acceptable to BH/CO Electric. The installing Party, at its own expense, shall inspect and test the Back-Up Metering upon installation and at least annually thereafter. The installing Party shall provide the other Party with advance notice of, and permit a representative of such other Party to witness and verify, such inspections and tests, provided, however, that such other Party shall not unreasonably interfere with or disrupt the activities of the installing Party and shall comply with all of relevant safety standards. Upon request, the installing Party shall perform additional inspections or tests of the Back-Up Metering and shall permit a qualified representative of the other Party to inspect, witness and verify the testing of the Back-Up Metering, provided, however, that such other Party shall not unreasonably interfere with or disrupt the activities of the installing Party and shall comply with all relevant safety standards. The actual expense of any such requested additional inspection or testing shall be borne by the Party requesting the test, unless, upon such inspection or testing, the Back-Up Metering is found to register inaccurately by more than the allowable limits established in this Article 5, in which event the expense of the requested additional inspection or testing shall be borne by Seller. If requested in writing, the installing Party shall provide copies of any inspection or testing reports to the other Party. (C) If any Electric Metering Devices, or the Back-Up Metering, are found to be defective or inaccurate outside the bounds of the selected device’s manufacturer’s performance standards, they shall be adjusted, repaired, replaced, or recalibrated as near as practicable to a condition of zero error by the Party owning such defective or inaccurate device and at that Party’s expense. 5.4 Adjustment for Inaccurate Meters. If an Electric Metering Device, or the Back-Up Metering, fails to register, or if the measurement made by an Electric Metering Device, or the Back-Up Metering, is found upon testing to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%), an adjustment shall be made correcting all measurements by the inaccurate or defective Electric Metering Device, or the Back-Up Metering, for both the amount of the inaccuracy and the period of the inaccuracy, in the following manner: (A) In the event that the Electric Metering Device is found to be defective or inaccurate, the Parties shall use the Back-Up Metering, if installed, to determine the amount of such inaccuracy, provided, however, that the Back-Up Metering has been tested and maintained in accordance with the provisions of this Article. If the Back-Up Metering is installed on the low side of Seller’s step-up transformer, the Back-Up Metering data shall be adjusted for losses. In the event that, neither Party installed Back-Up Metering, or Back-Up Metering is also found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%), the Parties shall estimate the amount of the necessary adjustment on the basis of deliveries of net capacity and energy from the Facility during periods of similar operating conditions when the Electric Metering Device was registering accurately. The adjustment shall be made for the period during which inaccurate measurements were made. (B) In the event that the Parties cannot agree on the actual period during which the inaccurate measurements were made, the period during which the measurements are to be adjusted shall be the shorter of (i) the last one-half of the period from the last previous test of the Electric Metering Device to the test that found the Electric Metering Device to be defective or inaccurate, or (ii) the one hundred eighty (180) Days immediately preceding the test that found the Electric Metering Device to be defective or inaccurate. (C) To the extent that the adjustment period covers a period of deliveries for which payment has already been made by BH/CO Electric, BH/CO Electric shall use the corrected measurements as determined in accordance with this Article to recompute the amount due for the period of the inaccuracy and shall subtract the previous payments by BH/CO Electric for this period from such recomputed amount. If the difference is a positive number, the difference shall be paid by BH/CO Electric to Seller; if the difference is a negative number, that difference shall be paid by Seller to BH/CO Electric, or at the discretion of BH/CO Electric, may take the form of an offset to payments due Seller by BH/CO Electric. Payment of such difference by the owing Party shall be made not later than thirty (30) Days after the owing Party receives notice of the amount due, unless BH/CO Electric elects payment via an offset. 5.5 Natural Gas Fuel Procurement and Delivery. (A) Seller acknowledges that BH/CO Electric is required to file a gas cost mitigation plan with the CPUC before January 1, 2012. Accordingly, all arrangements for the procurement and delivery of all natural gas fuel required for Seller to produce the Contract Energy dispatched by BH/CO Electric must be acceptable to the Parties. Such arrangements shall include all natural gas interconnection and metering arrangements required to interconnect the Facility to, and receive Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel from, upstream pipeline(s) at adequate delivery pressure and volume, and to fully operate the Facility turbine units, using such natural gas fuel, over the Commercial Operation period. Such arrangements shall further include the construction, operation and maintenance of the Natural Gas Interconnection Facilities and natural gas metering facilities, including any natural gas compression, regulation, heating and filter/separation equipment required to fully operate the Facility generating unit(s) over the Commercial Operation period using the Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel delivered to the Facility. If Seller elects to install other natural gas-fired equipment that is not used for the direct conversion of natural gas fuel to electric energy (such as natural gas-fired auxiliary boiler(s), natural gas in-line heater(s) used to heat the natural gas fuel, or building heating equipment), such arrangements shall also include the separate metering and supply of the natural gas fuel consumed by such natural gas-fired equipment. (B) All natural gas fuel delivered for the purpose of generating Contract Energy shall be Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel. (C) All arrangements for the procurement and delivery of natural gas shall be set forth in an addendum to this PPA (the “Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum”) to be designated as Exhibit N and to be executed no later than thirty (30) days prior to the date when BH/CO Electric elects to file its gas cost mitigation plan. All costs for procurement and delivery of natural gas shall be borne by Seller unless otherwise agreed to in writing by BH/CO Electric in the Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum. (D) Unless otherwise provided in the Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum, Seller shall be responsible for all volume confirmations, allocations and balancing functions with the applicable upstream pipeline, as well as gas regulation and maintenance and testing arrangements for all natural gas metering. Seller shall also be responsible for all natural gas physical flow activities, such as flow control, valve operation, and contacting the delivering pipeline to initiate gas flow to the Facility.
