Article 7 - Sale and Purchase of Capacity and Energy 7.1 Contract Capacity and Energy. (A) The Contract Capacity provided and sold by Seller and purchased by BH/CO Electric hereunder shall be all of the net generating capacity available at any time from the Facility at the Point of Delivery, not to exceed the Net Capability. The Contract Capacity purchased by BH/CO Electric shall include any and all uncommitted and undispatched capacity available from each Unit, which, in combination with the capacity that has been committed and dispatched by BH/CO Electric hereunder, shall not exceed the Net Capability. (B) The Contract Energy provided by Seller and received by BH/CO Electric hereunder shall be the metered, net energy output generated by the Contract Capacity as delivered and adjusted for losses to the Point of Delivery; less any such energy that has not been dispatched by BH/CO Electric; and less any Test Energy separately purchased by BH/CO Electric pursuant to paragraph 4.9(B) that has been uneconomically dispatched by BH/CO Electric at Seller’s request. For avoidance of any doubt, Seller shall sell to BH/CO Electric and BH/CO Electric shall purchase from Seller all such Contract Energy. In the event the net energy output exceeds the quantity dispatched by BH/CO Electric, Seller shall nevertheless be credited with the actual net energy output generated so long as such output is within a tolerance that complies with NERC or other applicable standards and BH/CO Electric has not given Seller notice to reduce such output to the dispatched quantity.
(C) Beginning on the Commercial Operation Date, Seller shall supply from the Facility and sell to BH/CO Electric, and BH/CO Electric shall receive and purchase, the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy, as specified in this Article 7. Seller shall deliver the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy to, and make such capacity and energy available for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric at, the Point of Delivery. To the extent each Unit is available to operate, all of the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy shall be made available for delivery to the Point of Delivery and receipt by BH/CO Electric as dispatched by BH/CO Electric under this PPA. Seller shall not curtail or interrupt deliveries of Contract Capacity or Contract Energy for economic reasons or any other reasons not expressly permitted under this PPA. 7.2 Excess Capacity and Excess Energy. The Parties acknowledge that during the Term, Seller may have available for sale commercially viable amounts of Excess Capacity and Excess Energy. Seller shall have the right to offer such Excess Capacity and Excess Energy for sale to BH/CO Electric but shall not have the right to offer such Excess Capacity or Excess Energy to other purchasers. Additionally, BH/CO Electric shall have the right to dispatch Excess Energy during the term of this PPA and shall pay the Contract Energy Price (CEP) set forth in Section 8.3 of this PPA for such Excess Energy together with the Variable Fuel Charge and Fixed Fuel Charge set forth in Section 8.3 attributable to such Excess Energy. 7.3 Dispatch. BH/CO Electric's GDPM operator shall have the right to determine the AGC control of each Unit, Unit starts, Unit shutdowns and loading levels associated with the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy. Nothing in this PPA shall be construed to require or permit BH/CO Electric to dispatch the Facility at below Minimum Loading. For any Unit trip, Seller shall restart the Unit in coordination with the GDPM in accordance with Good Utility Practices. 7.4 Operating Reserve. All Operating Reserve associated with the Contract Capacity shall be deemed to have been purchased by BH/CO Electric, shall be made available to BH/CO Electric as Operating Reserve, and shall be activated by Seller when needed and called upon by BH/CO Electric. Upon achieving the Commercial Operation Date, Seller shall maximize the Operating Reserve available to BH/CO Electric from the Contract Capacity, consistent with and subject to the Operating Standards. 7.5 Restriction of Contract Energy. (A) It is the expectation of the Parties that the amount of Contract Energy available for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric shall not be restricted, due to any Applicable Law, to less than that available from the Net Capability (“Planned Energy”) during any period of Commercial Operation. Unless required by Applicable Law, neither the Parties nor their Affiliates (including any person acting on their behalf) shall take any action that would result in or materially contribute to a restriction, under the Facility’s present or future permits, in the amount of Contract Energy available for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric to a level that is less than the Planned Energy during any period of Commercial Operation. (B) In the event that Changed Standards restrict the amount of electric energy that may be produced by the Units or the Facility and, as a result of such Changed Standards, Seller, at any time during Commercial Operation, restricts the amount of Contract Energy that is available for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric to an amount less than the Planned Energy (“Lost Energy”) or restricts BH/CO Electric’s AGC of the Contract Capacity, Seller shall reserve one hundred percent (100%) of the amount of electric energy that may be produced by the Facility, less that energy production needed for required testing and operation of the Facility, for the delivery of Contract Energy to BH/CO Electric. Nothing in this PPA shall be construed to create an obligation of Seller to operate the Facility, or permission for BH/CO Electric to dispatch Contract Energy, in violation of the Facility’s governmental permits. Nothing in this provision shall be construed to limit or modify BH/CO Electric’s rights and remedies under this PPA, including, but not limited to the right to receive Replacement Power Costs and the right to terminate under certain conditions as provided in this PPA. (C) If, as a result of the imposition of a Changed Standard because of the misconduct of Seller, (i) Seller is required to restrict the amount of energy that may be produced by the Facility, (ii) the amount of Contract Energy that is available for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric is restricted to an amount which is less than the Planned Energy, or (iii) Seller is required to restrict BH/CO Electric’s AGC of the Contract Capacity, such availability restrictions shall be reflected in the monthly Capacity Payment and/or Dispatchability Payment calculations specified in Sections 8.1 and 8.2 respectively. 7.6 Title and Risk of Loss. As between the Parties, Seller shall be deemed to be in control of the Contract Capacity, Contract Energy and Test Energy output from the Facility up to and until delivery and receipt at the Point of Delivery and BH/CO Electric shall be deemed to be in control of such capacity and energy from and after delivery and receipt at the Point of Delivery. Title and risk of loss related to the Contract Capacity, Contract Energy and Test Energy shall transfer from Seller to BH/CO Electric at the Point of Delivery. Article 8 - Payment Calculations 8.1 Payment for Contract Capacity. Commencing on the Commercial Operation Date, BH/CO Electric shall pay Seller a Monthly Capacity Payment for Contract Capacity based on the following formula: Monthly Capacity Payment = NC × CAF × CP, where: NC = Net Capability (as specified in Section 3.4) CAF = Capacity Availability Factor, Monthly Average not to exceed 1 = (AE + SME) / PE, where: AE = Available Energy, stated in Megawatt-hours (MWh), is the amount of energy associated with the Contract Capacity that is available from the Facility for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric, regardless of whether BH/CO Electric dispatches Contract Energy for receipt at that level, in the monthly billing period and the previous eleven monthly billing periods. The Contract Capacity will be considered to be available in any hour where: (i) the Facility is disconnected from BH/CO Electric’s system pursuant to an LGIA and the disconnection is not caused by actions of Seller or problems with the Facility; (ii) the Facility is unavailable due to BH/CO Electric’s failure to supply Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel to the Facility (if BH/CO Electric is responsible for supplying Acceptable Natural Gas Fuel pursuant to the Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum); (iii) the Facility cannot operate due to restrictions resulting from BH/CO Electric’s electric transmission constraints; or (iv) BH/CO Electric has curtailed or interrupted the delivery of capacity and energy from the Facility for any reason not arising from action of Seller or problems with the Facility. The Contract Capacity which is unavailable for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric will also be considered to be available for the purposes of determining Available Energy when, and only when, the Facility is restricted in operation to an amount which is less than the Planned Energy as a result of Changed Standards, other than Changed Standards imposed due to the misconduct of Seller. In the event that the Facility is restricted in operation to an amount which is less than the Planned Energy as a result of Changed Standards imposed due to the misconduct of Seller, the Contract Capacity shall be considered unavailable to the extent that Seller cannot deliver Contract Energy or Seller’s Replacement Power to BH/CO Electric in an amount equal to the Planned Energy set forth in Section 7.6. The Contract Capacity will also be considered to be unavailable for the purposes of determining Available Energy when, and to the extent that, (i) Seller is unable to provide or deliver such Contract Capacity and the associated energy due to an event of Force Majeure, not on BH/CO Electric’s side of the Point of Delivery, affecting Seller or the Facility, and (ii) Seller does not have Seller’s Replacement Power available for dispatch by BH/CO Electric. Available Energy shall be calculated as the sum, for all hours in the billing period, of the amount of energy associated with the Contract Capacity available during each individual hour. SME = Scheduled Maintenance Energy, stated in MWh, is the amount of energy associated with the Contract Capacity that is not available from the Facility for dispatch and receipt by BH/CO Electric, in the monthly billing period and the previous eleven monthly billing periods, due to Scheduled Outages/Deratings that meet the requirements for credited Scheduled Maintenance Energy specified in Section 10.1. Scheduled Maintenance Energy shall be calculated as the sum, for all hours in the billing period and the previous eleven monthly billing periods, of the amount of energy associated with the Contract Capacity that is unavailable during each individual hour due to a Scheduled Outage/Derating that meets the specified requirements for credited Scheduled Maintenance Energy. PE = Period Energy, stated in MWh, shall be calculated, for the monthly billing period and the previous eleven (11) monthly billing periods, as the product of the Net Capability and the total number of hours in the billing period and the previous eleven (11) monthly billing periods. For the first eleven (11) monthly billing periods of the Term, CAF shall be determined under the assumption that (i) the COD occurred eleven (11) months prior to the actual COD and (ii) for each of such months, CAF equals 1. For the last monthly billing period of the Term, the Monthly Capacity Payment will be decreased to the extent that, because CAF is determined on a rolling monthly basis, the Monthly Capacity Payments for the last eleven (11) monthly billing periods have failed to make BH/CO Electric whole for instances where CAF is less than 1 in any of the last eleven (11) months of the Term. If the application of the preceding sentence fails to make BH/CO Electric whole, then Seller will make BH/CO Electric whole by crediting the applicable amount against any other amount payable by BH/CO Electric to Seller under this PPA and, if necessary, by making a final CAF true-up payment to BH/CO Electric. CP = Capacity Price, stated in $/kW-month, shall be $14.62 for the entire Term. 8.2 Payment for Dispatchability. Commencing on the Commercial Operation Date or such later date when the provisions of Exhibit A have been satisfied including but not limited to the initial verification of compliance, BH/CO Electric shall pay Seller a monthly Dispatchability Payment (prorated to reflect the actual number of Days of Commercial Operation in the first and last monthly billing periods) based on the following formula: Monthly Dispatchability Payment = NC x DAF x $0.15/kW-month, where: NC = Net Capability (as specified in Section 3.4) DAF = Dispatch Availability Factor, Twelve (12) Month Rolling Average, where the factor is based on the number of hours the Facility is on AGC by BH/CO Electric, as determined by BH/CO Electric, and the number of hours the Facility is on line adjusted for Ramp Rate Availability. DAF is derived from the following formula: DAF = (Hours on-control / Hours on-line) × RAF, where: Hours on-control = the total number of hours during the monthly billing period and the preceding eleven (11) monthly billing periods when the Facility’s generating unit(s) are receiving and responding to dispatch pulses transmitted from BH/CO Electric’s GDPM. Any hour for which BH/CO Electric requests that the Contract Capacity be dispatched without AGC by BH/CO Electric will be counted as an Hour on-control so that the ratio of (Hours on-control/Hours on-line) will be one (1) for such hour. Hours on-line = the total number of hours during the monthly billing period and the preceding eleven (11) monthly billing periods when the Facility’s generating unit(s) are synchronized to Interconnection Provider’s System and available to generate electric energy. RAF = Ramp Rate Availability Factor, where RAF is determined by the following table subsequent to verification testing by BH/CO Electric as set forth in Exhibit A:
Tested Contract Capacity Ramp Rate Performance Per Unit RAF Contract Capacity ramps at a rate which is greater than or equal to one hundred percent (100%) of the rate set forth in Exhibit A under “Dispatchability Requirements”. 1.00 Contract Capacity ramps at a rate which is greater than or equal to seventy-five percent (75%), but less than one hundred percent (100%), of the rate set forth in Exhibit A under “Dispatchability Requirements”. 0.75 Contract Capacity ramps at a rate which is greater than or equal to fifty percent (50%), but less than seventy-five percent (75%), of the rate set forth in Exhibit A under “Dispatchability Requirements”. 0.50 Contract Capacity ramps at a rate which is less than fifty percent (50%) of the rate set forth in Exhibit A under “Dispatchability Requirements”. 0.00
For the eleven (11) monthly billing periods including and after the monthly billing period for which the first Dispatchability Payment is due, DAF shall be determined under the assumption that (i) Dispatchability Payments had been payble for the prior eleven (11) monthly billing periods and (ii) for each of such monthly billing periods, DAF equals 1. For the last monthly billing period of the Term, the Dispatchability Payment will be decreased to the extent that, because DAF is determined on a rolling monthly basis, the Monthly Dispatchability Payments for the last eleven (11) monthly billing periods have failed to make BH/CO Electric whole for instances where DAF is less than 1 in any of the last eleven (11) months of the Term. If the application of the preceding sentence fails to make BH/CO Electric whole, then Seller will make BH/CO Electric whole by crediting the applicable amount against any other amount payable by BH/CO Electric to Seller under this PPA and, if necessary, by making a final DAF true-up payment to BH/CO Electric. 8.3 Payment for Contract Energy. Commencing on the Commercial Operation Date, BH/CO Electric shall pay Seller a monthly energy payment for the Contract Energy that is dispatched by BH/CO Electric and delivered by Seller to the Point of Delivery during the billing month including any Seller’s Replacement Power that is dispatched by BH/CO Electric and delivered to BH/CO Electric during the billing month. If the Heat Rate Adjustment (“HRA”) results in a negative Energy Payment for any billing month, the negative balance shall be offset against the payments determined pursuant to Section 8.1. The monthly Energy Payment shall be determined by the following formula (except as to any Seller’s Replacement Power for which the monthly Energy Payment shall be determined pursuant to Section 8.9): Monthly payment for Contract Energy = (E x CEP) + VFC - HRA + FFC + FHC, where: E = Contract Energy, stated in MWh, which is dispatched by BH/CO Electric and delivered by Seller to the Point of Delivery during the billing month; CEP = Contract Energy Price which shall be the Variable O and M Price set forth below, expressed in $/MWh Commercial Operation Period Variable O and M Price Up to the first anniversary of the COD $2.90 Each year following an anniversary of the COD 3% increase over the prior year’s price
VFC = Variable Fuel Charge, determined as follows: All commodity and other costs incurred by Seller related to gas supply, delivery, procurement, and management that are derived from, or charged on, a volumetric basis for the purpose of generating electricity from the Facility. HRA = Heat Rate Adjustment, determined as a dollar amount pursuant to Section 8.4. FFC = Fixed Fuel Charge, determined as follows: All costs incurred by Seller related to gas supply, delivery, procurement, and management that are not derived from, or charged on, a volumetric basis but are incurred for the purpose of generating electricity from the Facility. FHC = Fired Hour Charge, which shall be the charge applied for any hour or portion of an hour that a combustion turbine engine at the Facility is directed to be fired or dispatched by BH/CO Electric. The Fired Hour Charge is $185.66 per engine-fired hour during the first year after COD. For subsequent years, the Fired Hour Charge shall escalate at 3% annually at every anniversary of the COD. 8.4 Heat Rate Adjustment to Payments. (A) If the Actual Net Heat Rate for the Facility is greater than the Predicted Net Heat Rate, the Heat Rate Adjustment, for the billing month following the heat rate test until the billing month following the next heat rate test, shall be used to reduce payments to Seller as specified in Section 8.3 and shall be determined by the following formula:
Heat Rate Adjustment = Variable Fuel Charge × (1 – (P/A)), where: “Variable Fuel Charge” is the amount set forth in Section 8.3. “P” is the Predicted Net Heat Rate (HHV) at the time of the most recent heat rate test; and “A” is the Actual Net Heat Rate (HHV) for the Facility as determined from the most recent heat rate test. (B) If the Actual Net Heat Rate for the Facility is less than ninety-seven percent (97%) of the Predicted Net Heat Rate, the Heat Rate Adjustment, for the billing month following the heat rate test until the billing month following next heat rate test, shall be used to increase payments to Seller as specified in Section 8.3 and shall be determined by the following formula: Heat Rate Adjustment = Variable Fuel Charge × (1 – [(P x 0.97)/A]), where: “Variable Fuel Charge” is the amount set forth in Section 8.3. “P” is the Predicted Net Heat Rate (HHV) at the time of the most recent heat rate test; and “A” is the Actual Net Heat Rate (HHV) for the Facility as determined from the most recent heat rate test. (C) If the Actual Net Heat Rate for the Facility is equal to or less than the Predicted Net Heat Rate and is equal to or greater than ninety-seven percent (97%) of the Predicted Net Heat Rate, the Heat Rate Adjustment, for the billing month following the heat rate test until the billing month following next heat rate test, shall be deemed to be zero dollars ($0.00) for the payment calculations specified in Section 8.3. 8.5 Heat Rate Testing. (A) The Actual Net Heat Rate shall be determined by heat rate testing at the maximum design load operation for the Facility turbine generator(s) with steam valves wide open to generate the total maximum output of the Facility at ambient conditions during the test, at an ambient temperature of not less than eighty-five ( degrees Fahrenheit ((85 ºF), with, if applicable, cooling of intake air. The results of such testing shall be adjusted to Reference Conditions using the final design correction curves for the Facility (specifically, the design correction curves reflecting expected Facility equipment performance after all equipment tuning and adjustments have been completed) to determine the Actual Net Heat Rate. For the purposes of heat rate testing and determination of the Actual Net Heat Rate, (i) fuel input shall be measured and adjusted, as necessary, for any natural gas fuel consumed by natural gas-fired equipment that is not used for the direct conversion of natural gas fuel to electric energy as discussed in paragraph 5.5(A) and (ii) electric output shall be measured at the Point of Delivery. Testing shall be performed in accordance with the current ASME test codes applicable to the Facility generating units, or in accordance with other mutually agreed upon test codes/procedures. Each Party shall have the right to request and schedule a heat rate test on a Business Day, not more often than once during any calendar year and upon written notice to the other Party at least sixty (60) Days prior to the Day of such test, pursuant to the procedures set forth in this Section. Seller shall perform the heat rate test under BH/CO Electric’s observation and concurrence. BH/CO Electric shall have the right to install, during the heat rate test and at BH/CO Electric’s expense, any temporary, redundant test equipment complying with the governing test codes, that BH/CO Electric deems necessary for the purpose of verifying test measurements obtained by, or on behalf of, Seller. To the extent practicable, heat rate tests shall be coordinated between the Parties and shall be scheduled to take place on normal dispatch Days. (B) Seller shall prepare and submit to BH/CO Electric for review and approval, at least thirty (30) Days prior to each heat rate test, the proposed heat rate test procedure. Such test procedure shall include (i) specification of the governing test codes, (ii) the extent to which the test codes will be followed, (iii) provisions for testing, including collection of test data, and (iv) methodology for calculating test results, including the planned method of adjusting the test net heat rate to each of the Reference Conditions. Seller shall be responsible for the full scope of heat rate testing, including, furnishing the test instrumentation, set-up, data gathering, fuel analysis, data analysis and the issuance of a final report. (C) Within sixty (60) Days following performance of each heat rate test, Seller shall provide to BH/CO Electric for review and approval (i) all raw test data, calculations, fuel analyses and a final test report, in written and, to the extent possible, electronic format, (ii) all as-built equipment specifications, correction curves, equations and other information necessary for review of the heat rate test results that have not been previously submitted to BH/CO Electric, and (iii) a fully functioning electronic model, in Gate-cycle or a similar program, that BH/CO Electric can use to verify Seller’s calculations of, and adjustments to, test data. The final test report shall include clear and complete explanations of the calculations resulting in the test net heat rate and the adjustment of the test net heat rate to each of the Reference Conditions. Uncertainty, as defined in the ASME power test codes, shall be used to adjust heat rate test results. (D) In connection with any heat rate test, BH/CO Electric may also require Seller to perform heat rate testing between 50 MW and 100 MW for each Unit for the sole purpose of developing an accurate dispatch heat rate curve for each possible Facility operating configuration. (E) Seller shall notify BH/CO Electric of any generation equipment tuning and adjustment that is reasonably likely to materially impact the heat rate performance of the Facility or the accuracy of the correction curves utilized to adjust the results of the most recent heat rate test. Upon such notification, BH/CO Electric may require Seller to perform additional heat rate testing of the Facility and provide new correction curves that reflect the actual post-tuning condition of the Facility equipment. (F) Seller shall perform the initial heat rate test on or before the first August 31st following the Commercial Operation Date. If the initial heat rate test is performed after the Commercial Operation Date, the Actual Net Heat Rate resulting from such initial heat rate test shall apply retroactively from the Commercial Operation Date for the purposes of determining the Heat Rate Adjustment pursuant to Section 8.4. The heat rate test performed by Seller, or on behalf of Seller, prior to Seller’s acceptance of the Facility’s generating units and auxiliary equipment may constitute the initial heat rate test, provided, that such test is performed in accordance with all the requirements for heat rate testing set forth in this Section. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if Seller elects to establish such Facility equipment acceptance heat rate test as the initial heat rate test under this PPA, the requirement that the heat rate test be performed at an ambient temperature of not less than eighty-five degrees Fahrenheit (85 ºF) shall be waived for such initial heat rate test. 8.6 Payment for Turbine Starts. Commencing on the Commercial Operation Date, BH/CO Electric shall pay Seller a Monthly Turbine Start Payment. The Monthly Turbine Start Payment shall be based on the following formula: Monthly Turbine Start Payment = (N-120) x TSP, where: N = Number of Successful Combustion Turbine Starts during the billing month; TSP = Turbine Start Price, which shall be $1,000.00 The Parties recognize that the Facility is intended to be operated as a baseload facility and that it will not be designed for routine shutdown. For clarity, BH/CO Electric shall not be entitled to payment or a credit if the Monthly Turbine Start Payments determined in accordance with this Section 8.6 is a negative number. 8.7 Fixed O and M Charge. Commencing on the COD, BH/CO Electric shall pay to Seller, in monthly installments, a Fixed O and M Charge, stated in $/kW-year. The Fixed O and M Charge shall be calculated as the product of $41.55 and the Net Capability. On every anniversary of the COD, the Fixed O and M Charge shall escalate by three percent (3%). 8.8 Governmental Imposition Charge. By no later than June 1 of each calendar year during the Term, Seller shall deliver to BH/CO Electric a statement that sets forth its determination of the amount, whether positive or negative, of the Governmental Impositions for the preceding year, together with reasonable supporting documentation (the “Governmental Imposition Charge”). Upon request by BH/CO Electric, Seller shall provide to BH/CO Electric such data and other information as may be reasonably necessary to allow BH/CO Electric to confirm Seller’s calculation of Governmental Imposition Charges. Seller shall have a duty to use commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate Governmental Imposition Charges. Subject to the foregoing duty to mitigate and notwithstanding any other provisions of this PPA to the contrary, the Governmental Imposition Charge will be payable by BH/CO Electric to Seller (if the Governmental Imposition Charge is positive), or by Seller to BH/CO Electric (if the Governmental Imposition Charge is negative), in equal monthly installments over the twelve (12) consecutive months beginning with July of the year in which such statement is delivered (or such fewer number of months to the end of the Term). In the event and to the extent that any Governmental Imposition Charges that are made during the last ten (10) years of the Term benefit Seller (or any successor owner of the Facility) following the Term, Seller shall repay or shall cause such successor to repay such benefits to BH/CO Electric as and when realized, valued on a quantum meruit basis. 8.9 Seller’s Replacement Power. Seller has the option under this PPA to deliver Seller’s Replacement Power prior to the Commercial Operation Date, as provided in paragraph 4.1(B) and Section 12.4. Additionally, as provided in Sections 8.1 and 8.3, Seller has the option under this PPA to deliver Seller’s Replacement Power. The price payable for Seller’s Replacement Power shall be as set forth in this Article 8 as if such capacity and energy had been delivered from the Facility, such price to be determined under the assumptions and otherwise in the manner set forth in Exhibit J to this PPA, and Seller shall be responsible for all incremental costs incurred (including any applicable FERC approved tariff charges for transmission, scheduling and ancillary services) in delivering such capacity and energy to the Point of Delivery or such other locations. Article 9 - Billing and Payment 9.1 Billing Invoices. (A) The billing period shall be the calendar month. No later than ten (10) Business Days after the end of the calendar month, Seller shall provide the information specified in paragraph 10.3(B) and Section 13.5 and an invoice showing the payment amount due Seller by BH/CO Electric for the services provided by Seller and purchased by BH/CO Electric, under this PPA, during the previous calendar month billing period. Seller’s invoice shall be in such form and shall be delivered by such means as BH/CO Electric may reasonably request from time to time. The invoice will show metered energy received at the Point of Delivery from the Facility, any Seller’s Replacement Power received during the calendar month, all billing parameters, rates and factors, and any other data reasonably pertinent to the calculation of monthly payments due to Seller. BH/CO Electric shall not be limited to Seller’s reported operational data and may make its own calculations on the basis of all information available to BH/CO Electric, including results of capacity tests, results of ramp rate tests, and Facility responses to requests for changes in operation. (B) If BH/CO Electric disputes any amount in the statement provided by Seller, BH/CO Electric shall provide Seller with an explanation of the items in dispute, as well as all supporting documentation upon which BH/CO Electric relies to dispute Seller’s invoice. Billing disputes shall be resolved in accordance with Section 9.5. 9.2 Metered Billing Data. All billing data based on metered deliveries to the Point of Delivery shall be collected by the Electric Metering Device(s) in accordance with Article 5. All billing data based on metered deliveries of any Seller’s Replacement Power shall be collected by appropriate electric metering devices. 9.3 Reactive Power Service Compensation. The Parties recognize that, although Seller's obligation to provide reactive power service from the Facility to the Interconnection Provider's System and any compensation Seller receives for such reactive power service are to be set forth in the LGIA, the compensation that Seller receives from BH/CO Electric under this PPA includes full compensation for the fixed and variable costs associated with providing such reactive power service. Therefore, Seller shall credit BH/CO Electric monthly, as a separate line item reduction to Seller's invoice, for any compensation that Seller receives, apart from that provided under this PPA, for the provision of reactive power service from the Facility during the Term of this PPA. Such credit shall differentiate, if possible, between compensation provided for the fixed costs and the variable costs of providing reactive power service. 9.4 Payments. Unless otherwise specified herein, payments due under this PPA shall be due and payable by check or by electronic funds transfer, as designated by the owed Party, on or before the fifteenth (15th) Business Day following receipt of the billing invoice. Remittances received by mail will be considered to have been paid when due if the postmark indicates the payment was mailed on or before the fifteenth (15th) Business Day following receipt of the billing invoice. If the amount due is not paid on or before the due date, a late payment charge shall be applied to the unpaid balance and shall be added to the next billing statement. Such late payment charge shall be calculated based on an annual interest rate equal to one hundred twenty-five percent (125%) of the LIBOR three-month rate published on the date of the invoice in The Wall Street Journal (or, if The Wall Street Journal is not published on that Day, the next succeeding date of publication). If the due date occurs on a Day that is not a Business Day, the late payment charge shall begin to accrue on the next succeeding Business Day. 9.5 Billing Disputes. (A) Either Party may dispute invoiced amounts, but shall pay to the other Party at least the undisputed portion of invoiced amounts on or before the invoice due date. To resolve any billing dispute, the Parties shall use the procedures set forth in Section 13.9. When the billing dispute is resolved, the Party owing shall pay the amount owed within five (5) Business Days of the date of such resolution, with late payment interest charges calculated on the amount owed in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.4. (B) In the event that (i) the creditworthiness of one Party (the “Affected Party”) becomes impaired to such extent that the other Party (the “Claimant”) has objective, commercially reasonable grounds to believe that the Affected Party’s continued ability to perform this PPA as and when due is in material doubt, and (ii) there exist one or more bona fide billing or other disputes under this PPA, in connection with which the Claimant alleges in good faith that the Affected Party owes the Claimant more than $1,000,000 in the aggregate (net of undisputed amounts owed by the Claimant to the Affected Party), the Affected Party shall, within thirty (30) Days following request therefor by the Claimant, deposit the net amount in dispute into a separate escrow account at a mutually acceptable Issuer (the “Escrow Account”) pursuant to a mutually acceptable escrow agreement consistent with this Section. The Escrow Account shall be owned by the Affected Party but the Claimant shall hold a first and exclusive perfected security interest therein to secure the obligation of the Affected Party to pay the amount(s) in dispute if and to the extent that the dispute(s) are eventually resolved in favor of the Claimant. If, as and when the related disputes are resolved, amounts owed to the Claimant (if any) shall be paid out of the Escrow Account and the balance shall be released to the Affected Party. Funds held in any Escrow Account may be deposited in a money-market fund, short-term treasury obligations, investment-grade commercial paper and other liquid investment-grade investments with maturities of three months or less, with all investment income thereon to be taxable to, and to accrue for the benefit of, the Affected Party. All fees and expenses of the Issuer holding any Escrow Account shall be paid by the Claimant. 9.6 Netting. (A) BH/CO Electric at any time may offset against any and all amounts that may be due and owed to Seller under this PPA, any and all liquidated amounts, including damages and other payments, that are owed by Seller to BH/CO Electric pursuant to this PPA or are past due under other accounts or agreements Seller has with BH/CO Electric for other goods or services. Undisputed and non-offset portions of amounts invoiced under this PPA shall be paid on or before the due date or shall be subject to the late payment interest charges set forth in Section 9.4. (B) Seller and BH/CO Electric agree that they will net their obligations to each other under this PPA. Such amounts will be aggregated and Seller and BH/CO Electric will discharge their obligations to pay through netting of payments. If the amounts owed by BH/CO Electric or Seller to the other are equal, neither shall be required to make payment under this PPA. Article 10 - Operations and Maintenance 10.1 Scheduled Maintenance. (A) Seller shall provide a schedule of the expected Scheduled Outages/Deratings for the Facility (“Maintenance Schedule”) for the first Commercial Operation Year prior to January 1, 2012. Thereafter, on or before every October 1, Seller shall submit an annual Maintenance Schedule for the next successive Commercial Operation Year. Each Scheduled Outage/Derating on each Maintenance Schedule shall include the start time and expected duration of the outage. On or before October 1, 2012 and every October 1 thereafter, Seller shall also supply a long-term Maintenance Schedule that will encompass the following four Commercial Operation Years. Any change in the annual Maintenance Schedule, by either Party, shall be furnished to the other Party with advance notice. Minimum advance notice of any change in the Maintenance Schedule is as follows: Scheduled Outage Expected Duration Advance Notice Required (1) Less than 2 Days at least 3 Days (2) 2 to 5 Days at least 14 Days (3) Major overhauls (over 5 Days) at least 180 Days
(B) Seller shall not schedule any Scheduled Outage/Deratings, excluding outages associated with Emergencies and Forced Outages, during any Business Day of an On Peak Month without the prior written approval of BH/CO Electric. (C) BH/CO Electric shall provide Seller the opportunity to use 430 MWh of Scheduled Maintenance Energy (“SME”) per MW of Net Capability during each Commercial Operation Year as a credit towards Seller’s Capacity Availability Factor (“CAF”) pursuant to the payment calculation specified in Section 8.1, provided, that such SME is scheduled in advance with BH/CO Electric pursuant to this Article and approved in writing by BH/CO Electric prior to Seller’s use of such SME. If Seller uses less than 430 MWh of SME per MW of Net Capability in a Commercial Operation Year, Seller may carry over for use in the next Commercial Operation Year unused SME as additional credit towards Seller’s CAF during the next Commercial Operation Year, provided, that such SME carried over shall also be scheduled in advance with BH/CO Electric pursuant to this Article and approved in writing by BH/CO Electric prior to Seller’s use of such SME, and provided further, that the total SME per MW of Net Capability that may be accumulated by Seller for use in any Commercial Operation Year, beginning with the second Commercial Operation Year and including carry over SME, shall not exceed 860 MWh of SME per MW of Net Capability for that Commercial Operation Year. SME may not be advanced from future Commercial Operation Years. For any Commercial Operation Year that is a partial calendar year, the SME amounts in this paragraph 10.1(C) will be pro-rated accordingly. (D) To the extent practicable and consistent with other provisions of this PPA, Scheduled Outages/Deratings shall be coordinated between the Parties and shall be scheduled to take place during calendar months that are not On-Peak Months. Notwithstanding the foregoing, BH/CO Electric shall have the right to change the start date of any Scheduled Outage/Derating proposed by Seller in the Maintenance Schedule provided to BH/CO Electric pursuant to paragraph 10.1(A); provided, however, that (1) BH/CO Electric furnishes Seller with advance notice of the change in accordance with the advance notice requirements set forth in paragraph 10.1(A), and (2) the changed start date must be within forty-five (45) Days, earlier or later, of the start date set forth for such Outage/Derating in the most recent Maintenance Schedule provided by Seller. (E) Not less than twelve (12) hours prior to commencement of any Scheduled Outage/Derating previously scheduled by Seller or BH/CO Electric in accordance with paragraphs 10.1(A) through 10.1(D), BH/CO Electric may request, including by phone, that Seller defer such Scheduled Outage/Derating. Subject to the Operating Standards, Seller shall comply with any such request and reschedule such deferred Scheduled Outage/Derating to a subsequent date mutually agreed upon between the Parties. In connection with any such request by BH/CO Electric for deferral of a Scheduled Outage/Derating, Seller shall provide to BH/CO Electric, in advance if reasonably practicable, a non-binding good faith estimate of the incremental direct costs to be incurred by Seller in order to comply with such request. If BH/CO Electric desires Seller to incur such incremental costs at BH/CO Electric’s expense, BH/CO Electric shall promptly advise Seller to that effect and such revised schedule shall be binding upon Seller. Seller may then invoice BH/CO Electric for, and BH/CO Electric shall pay Seller for, all of the actual incremental direct costs incurred by Seller in connection with such deferral and rescheduling of the Scheduled Outage/Derating. Start up of the Facility will be governed by Section 10.2 and charges for start up will be governed by Section 8.8. 10.2 Facility Operation. Seller shall staff, control, and operate the Facility consistent at all times with Good Utility Practice(s) and the Operating Procedures developed pursuant to Section 10.5. Personnel capable of starting, operating, and stopping the Facility shall be continuously available at the Facility during all hours of every Day during Commercial Operation. (A) Facility Operating Standards. The Facility shall be operated, maintained and managed by Seller in accordance with: (1) All Applicable Laws, including the requirements of any Governmental Authorities and applicable reliability standards; (2) Good Utility Practices; (3) All safety, fire, protection and other requirements of applicable insurance policies then in effect; and (4) In all material respects, the warranties, operating manuals and procedures for the Facility (items (1) through (4), collectively, the "Operating Standards"). (B) Operation, Maintenance and Asset Management for the Facility. Seller shall perform or cause to be performed all services required to operate, maintain and manage the Facility in accordance with the Operating Standards, including: (1) Staffing, training and managing the operating personnel; (2) Performing routine preventative and corrective maintenance of the equipment at the Facility to optimize equipment reliability and availability; (3) Implementing and maintaining adequate spare parts and control system; (4) Coordinating the activities of suppliers of goods and services to the Facility; (5) Maintaining logs and records of Facility operations with record retention procedures acceptable to BH/CO Electric; (6) Developing safety plans and procedures for all operating and maintenance contractors and personnel on the Site; (7) Planning scheduled outages of the Facility in accordance with this PPA and Good Utility Practices; and (8) Making all Capital Improvements, subject to paragraph 10.2(E) below, and performing all other work necessary to operate, maintain and manage the Facility for the optimal performance and availability of the Facility during the Term. (C) Operating Costs. Seller shall promptly pay all ownership costs, taxes, fixed costs, variable costs, labor costs, employee benefit and retirement costs, operating costs, maintenance decommissioning costs and costs of Capital Improvements associated with the Facility, and any fines imposed by Governmental Authorities associated with the operation of the Facility. (D) Communications. Seller shall provide and maintain a 24x7 real time communication link to the GDPM and be available to address all operational matters arising at the Facility. (E) Capital Improvements. Any Capital Improvements affixed to, installed on, added to, or incorporated into the Facility by Seller shall not reduce the Net Capability of the Facility, unless otherwise required by Applicable Law. All Capital Improvements shall be completed in accordance with Good Utility Practices and with reasonable dispatch. 10.3 Outage and Performance Reporting. Seller shall comply with all current NERC and BH/CO Electric generating unit outage reporting requirements, as they may be revised from time to time, and as they apply to the Facility, including the following: (A) When Forced Outages occur, Seller shall notify BH/CO Electric’s GDPM of the existence, nature, start time, and expected duration of the Forced Outage as soon as practical, but in no event later than one (1) hour after the Forced Outage occurs. Seller shall promptly inform BH/CO Electric’s GDPM of changes in the expected duration of the Forced Outage unless relieved of this obligation by BH/CO Electric’s GDPM for the duration of each Forced Outage; (B) Seller shall report to BH/CO Electric information on Facility performance during a calendar month within ten (10) Business Days after the end of the calendar month. For each turbine generator, and using definitions provided by, or consistent with, the NERC Generation Availability Data System (“GADS”) Manual, or any successor document, the data reported shall include planned derated hours, unplanned derated hours, average derated kW from Net Capability during the derated hours, scheduled maintenance hours, average derated kW during scheduled maintenance hours, the number of turbine starts, hours on-control and hours on-line; and (C) In addition to the foregoing notification, should any Forced Outage, shutdown or derating of the Facility occur during an Elevated System Condition, Seller shall promptly conduct a root cause analysis and take reasonable corrective action to prevent reoccurrences. Such corrective action may include, but is not limited to, whether protective modifications to the Facility, additional operating or maintenance procedures and other appropriate preventative measures in accordance with Good Utility Practices and shall be at Seller's cost and expense. As soon as commercially practicable, Seller shall diligently complete such analysis and corrective actions and provide to BH/CO Electric a written report containing such analysis and a summary of the corrective action taken or to be taken. 10.4 Net Capacity Testing. Seller represents its best projection of the Facility’s net dependable capability to be 100 MW per Unit (200 MW total). To determine the net dependable capability of the Facility, Seller shall cause a capacity test of the Facility (“Test”) to be performed in accordance with the procedures identified in BH/CO Electric’s Capacity Test Requirements, as such may be updated or revised from time to time by BH/CO Electric in order to comply with the requirements of Governmental Authorities. A copy of the current Capacity Test Requirements is attached hereto as Exhibit D. Seller shall cause the initial Test to be performed no later than the first August 31 after the Commercial Operation Date is achieved. Each Party shall bear its own costs of conducting an initially scheduled Test, but if a subsequent or rescheduled Test is required, such subsequent or rescheduled Test shall be at Seller’s expense in accordance with Exhibit D. A Test result shall not change the Net Capability. 10.5 Operating Committee and Operating Procedures. (A) BH/CO Electric and Seller shall each appoint one representative and one alternate representative to act in matters relating to the Parties’ performance obligations under this PPA and to develop operating arrangements for the generation, delivery and receipt of electric capacity and energy hereunder. Such representatives shall constitute the Operating Committee. The Parties shall notify each other in writing of such appointments and any changes thereto. The Operating Committee shall have no authority to modify the terms or conditions of this PPA. (B) Prior to the Commercial Operation Date, the Operating Committee shall develop mutually agreeable written Operating Procedures which shall include method of day to day communications; metering, telemetering, telecommunications, and data acquisition procedures; key personnel list for applicable BH/CO Electric and Seller operating centers; operations and maintenance scheduling and reporting; daily capacity and energy reports; unit operations log; and such other matters as may be mutually agreed upon by the Parties. 10.6 Access to Facility. Appropriate representatives of BH/CO Electric shall at all reasonable times, including weekends and nights, and with reasonable prior notice, have access to the Facility to read meters and to perform all inspections and operational reviews as may be appropriate to facilitate the performance of this PPA, and, if applicable, to maintain and service any equipment owned by BH/CO Electric at the Facility. While at the Facility, such representatives shall observe such reasonable safety precautions as may be required by Seller and shall conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the operation of the Facility. 10.7 Reliability Standards. Seller shall operate the Facility in a manner that complies with all applicable national and regional reliability standards, including standards set by BH/CO Electric, the ERO, FERC, NERC and the CPUC, or any successor agencies setting reliability standards for the operation of generation facilities. To the extent that Seller’s failure to operate the Facility in compliance with such standards contributes in whole or in part to circumstancing resulting in monetary penalties being assessed to BH/CO Electric, the ERO or any successor agency for lack of compliance with reliability standards, Seller shall reimburse BH/CO Electric for its contributory share of such monetary penalties. Article 11 - Security for Performance 11.1 Seller’s Security Fund. (A) Seller shall establish, fund, and maintain a Security Fund, pursuant to the provisions of this Article 11, which shall be available to pay any amount due BH/CO Electric pursuant to this PPA. The Security Fund shall also provide security to BH/CO Electric to cover damages should the Facility fail to achieve the Commercial Operation Milestone or be available at any times required under this PPA or otherwise not operate in accordance with this PPA, subject to the provisions and limitations in Article 12. Seller shall establish the Security Fund at a level of $125/kW of Net Capability no later than sixty (60) Days following the date of this PPA, and shall maintain the Security Fund at such required level throughout the remainder of the Term. Seller shall replenish the Security Fund to the applicable required level specified in this Section within fifteen (15) Business Days after any draw on the Security Fund by BH/CO Electric. (B) In addition to any other remedy available to it, BH/CO Electric may, before or after termination of this PPA, draw from the Security Fund such amounts as are necessary to recover amounts owing to it pursuant to this PPA, including, any damages due to BH/CO Electric and any amounts for which BH/CO Electric is entitled to indemnification under this PPA. BH/CO Electric may, in its sole discretion, draw all or any part of such amounts due to it from any form of security to the extent available pursuant to this Section, and from all such forms, and in any sequence BH/CO Electric may select. Any failure to draw upon the Security Fund or other security for any damages or other amounts due to BH/CO Electric shall not prejudice BH/CO Electric’s rights to recover such damages or amounts in any other manner. (C) Except as otherwise provided in subparagraph (3) below, the Security Fund shall be maintained at Seller’s expense, shall be originated by or deposited in a financial institution or company (“Issuer”) acceptable to BH/CO Electric, and shall be in the form of one or more of the following: (1) An irrevocable standby letter of credit or a performance bond, in the form and substance of Exhibit I and acceptable to BH/CO Electric, from an Issuer with an unsecured bond rating (unenhanced by third-party support) equivalent to A- or better as determined by both Standard and Poor’s and Moody’s (or if either one or both are not available, equivalent ratings from alternate rating sources acceptable to BH/CO Electric). In addition, if such unsecured bond rating of the Issuer is exactly equivalent to A-, the Issuer must not be on credit watch or have a negative outlook by a rating agency. Security provided in this form shall be consistent with this PPA and include a provision for at least thirty (30) Days advance notice to BH/CO Electric of any expiration or earlier termination of the security so as to allow BH/CO Electric sufficient time to exercise its rights under said security if Seller fails to extend or replace the security. The form of such security must meet BH/CO Electric’s requirements to ensure that claims or draw-downs can be made unilaterally by BH/CO Electric in accordance with the terms of this PPA. Such security must be issued for a minimum term of three hundred and sixty (360) Days. Seller shall cause the renewal or extension of the security for additional consecutive terms of three hundred and sixty (360) Days or more (or, if shorter, the remainder of the Term) no later than thirty (30) Days prior to each expiration date of the security. If the security is not renewed or extended as required herein, BH/CO Electric shall have the right to draw immediately upon the security and to place the amounts so drawn, at Seller’s cost and with Seller’s funds, in an interest bearing escrow account in accordance with sub-paragraph (2) below, until and unless Seller provides a substitute form of such security meeting the requirements of this Article 11. Security in the form of an irrevocable standby letter of credit shall be governed by the Uniform Customs and Practice for Documentary Credits (2007 Revision), International Chamber of Commerce Brochure No. 600 (the "UCP"), except to the extent that the terms of the letter of credit are inconsistent with the provisions of the UCP, including Articles 13(b) and 17 of the UCP, in which case the terms of the letter of credit shall govern. (2) United States currency, deposited with an Issuer, in which BH/CO Electric holds a first and exclusive perfected security interest, either: (i) in an account under which BH/CO Electric is designated as beneficiary with sole authority to draft from the account or otherwise access the security; or (ii) held by Issuer as escrow agent with instructions to pay claims made by BH/CO Electric pursuant to this PPA, such instructions to be in a form satisfactory to BH/CO Electric. Security provided in this form shall include a requirement for immediate notice to BH/CO Electric from Issuer and Seller in the event that the sums held as security in the account or trust do not at any time meet the required level for the Security Fund as set forth in this Section 11.1. Funds held in the account may be deposited in a money-market fund, short-term treasury obligations, investment-grade commercial paper and other liquid investment-grade investments with maturities of three months or less, with all investment income thereon to be taxable to, and to accrue for the benefit of, Seller. After the Commercial Operation Date is achieved, annual account sweeps for recovery of interest earned by the Security Fund shall be allowed by Seller. At such times as the balance in the escrow account exceeds the amount of Seller’s obligation to provide security hereunder, BH/CO Electric shall remit to Seller on demand any excess in the escrow account above Seller’s obligations. (3) A guaranty substantially in the form of Exhibit K, from Black Hills Corporation or an Issuer with an investment grade credit rating as determined by both Standard and Poor’s and Moody’s (or if either one or both are not available, equivalent ratings from alternate rating sources acceptable to BH/CO Electric). In addition, if such Issuer’s credit rating is the lowest investment grade credit rating, the Issuer must not be on credit watch or have a negative outlook by a rating agency. BH/CO Electric may reevaluate from time to time the value of any guaranty posted by Seller for possible downgrade or for other negative circumstances. If the credit rating of an Issuer is downgraded or BH/CO Electric otherwise has commercially reasonable grounds to believe that there has been a material adverse change in the creditworthiness of an Issuer, then Seller shall be required to convert the guarantee provided by such Issuer to a Security Fund instrument meeting the criteria set forth in either sub-paragraph (1) or sub-paragraph (2) above no later than thirty (30) Days after receiving notice from BH/CO Electric that such conversion is required pursuant to this paragraph. Seller may change the form of the Security Fund at any time and from time to time upon reasonable prior notice to BH/CO Electric, but the Security Fund must at all times be consistent with the foregoing. (D) Promptly (i) following the end of the Term and the completion of all of Seller’s obligations under this PPA, or (ii) upon BH/CO Electric’s exercise of its right to terminate this PPA pursuant to Article 6, BH/CO Electric shall release the balance of the Security Fund (including any accumulated interest, if applicable) to Seller. (E) Seller shall reimburse BH/CO Electric for the incremental direct expenses (including the reasonable fees and expenses of counsel) incurred by BH/CO Electric in connection with the preparation, negotiation, execution and/or release of any security instruments, and other related documents, used by Seller to establish and maintain the Security Fund pursuant to Seller’s obligations under this Section 11.1. 11.2 Additional Security. (A) No later than thirty (30) Days following satisfaction (or if applicable, waiver by BH/CO Electric) of the conditions precedent set forth in Article 6 above, Seller shall execute and record a mortgage on the Facility substantially in the form of Exhibit L hereto (the “Subordinated Mortgage”). The Subordinated Mortgage shall be given to secure Seller’s continuing performance and any amounts that may be owed by Seller to BH/CO Electric pursuant to this PPA, including, without limitation, any damages excluded from the limitation on Seller’s liability for the limited purposes set forth in paragraphs 12.6(A) through (F). In addition, Seller agrees to execute and file such Uniform Commercial Code financing statements and to take such further action and execute such further instruments as shall reasonably be required by BH/CO Electric to confirm and continue the validity, priority, and perfection of the Subordinated Mortgage. (B) Seller agrees, and shall cause the Facility Lender to agree and the Financing Documents to provide, (i) that the lien of the Subordinated Mortgage shall be subordinate to the lien of the Facility Lender, and (ii) that, as long as BH/CO Electric is not in material default of its obligations under this PPA, the Facility and any party taking possession of the Facility through the exercise of the Facility Lender’s rights and remedies shall remain subject to the terms of this PPA (including the obligation to reinstate the Subordinated Mortgage, subject to the terms of this Section 11.2, following any foreclosure by the Facility Lender) and shall assume all of Seller’s obligations hereunder, both prospective and accrued, including the obligation to cure any then-existing defaults capable of cure by performance or the payment of money damages. Seller shall not pledge or assign, or cause or permit to be pledged or assigned, any stock or ownership interest in Seller as collateral to any party other than the Facility Lender without the prior consent of BH/CO Electric. (C) The granting of the Subordinated Mortgage shall not be to the exclusion of, nor be construed to limit, the amount of any further claims, causes of action or other rights accruing to BH/CO Electric by reason of any breach or default by Seller under this PPA or the early termination of this PPA as provided for herein. The Subordinated Mortgage shall be discharged and released, and BH/CO Electric shall take any steps reasonably required by Seller to effect and record such discharge and release, upon the expiration of the Term of this PPA, including any extension of the Term, and satisfaction by Seller of all obligations hereunder. (D) Seller shall reimburse BH/CO Electric for the incremental direct expenses (including, without limitation, the reasonable fees and expenses of counsel) incurred by BH/CO Electric in connection with the preparation, negotiation, execution and/or the discharge and release of the Subordinated Mortgage and any other documents evidencing the Subordinated Mortgage. 11.3 BH/CO Electric’s Security Fund. BH/CO Electric shall establish, fund and maintain a Security Fund in the amount of Ten Million Dollars ($10,000,000.00) which shall be available to pay any amount due Seller pursuant to this PPA. Except as otherwise provided as to subparagraph (3) below, such Security Fund shall be maintained at BH/CO Electric’s expense, shall be originated by an Issuer acceptable to Seller and shall be in the form of (1) an irrevocable standby letter of credit or a performance bond that complies with paragraph 11.1(C)(1) above; (2) United States currency that complies with paragraph 11.1(C)(2) above; or (3) a guaranty from Black Hills corporation or an Issuer that complies with paragraph 11.1(C)(3) above. BH/CO Electric may change the form of the Security Fund at any time and from time to time upon reasonable prior notice to Seller, but the Security Fund must at all times be consistent with the foregoing. Article 12 - Default and Remedies 12.1 Events of Default of Seller. (A) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of Seller upon its occurrence and no cure period shall be applicable: (1) Seller’s dissolution or liquidation; (2) Seller’s assignment of this PPA, or any of its rights hereunder, for the benefit of creditors (except for an assignment to the Facility Lender as security under the Financing Documents as permitted by this PPA); (3) Seller’s filing of a voluntary petition in bankruptcy or insolvency or for reorganization or arrangement under the bankruptcy laws of the United States or under any insolvency act of any State, or Seller voluntarily taking advantage of any such law or act by answer or otherwise; (4) The sale by Seller to a third party, or diversion by Seller for any use, of Contract Capacity or Contract Energy dedicated to BH/CO Electric by Seller other than in mitigation of damages for any breach by BH/CO Electric of this PPA; or (5) Seller’s actual fraud, tampering with BH/CO Electric-owned facilities or other material intentional misrepresentation or misconduct in connection with this PPA or the operation of the Facility that has a material adverse effect on BH/CO Electric. (B) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of Seller upon its occurrence but shall be subject to cure within thirty (30) Days (or, if only curable by performance, rather than the payment of money damages, such longer period as may be reasonably required to effect such a cure, provided that Seller commences the cure within such thirty (30) Day period and diligently pursues such cure to conclusion thereafter) after the date of written notice from BH/CO Electric to Seller (and, if applicable, the Facility Lender pursuant to Section 12.2) as provided for in Section 13.1: (1) Seller’s Abandonment of construction or operation of the Facility; (2) Seller’s failure, after the twelfth (12th) full month following the Commercial Operation Date, to maintain a CAF, pursuant to Section 8.1, greater than seventy percent (70%) on a twelve-month rolling average basis; provided, that to the extent such failure of performance is attributable to an event of Force Majeure, the contribution of such event of Force Majeure to such failure of performance shall be eliminated from the CAF calculation for the purpose of, and only for the purpose of, establishing an Event of Default of Seller pursuant to this paragraph 12.1(B)(3), and provided further, that the event of Force Majeure contributing, in whole or in part, to such failure of performance is subject to the provisions of Section 14.3; (3) Seller’s failure to establish and maintain the funding of the Security Fund in accordance with Section 11.1; (4) Seller’s failure to comply with the requirements of Section 11.2; (5) Seller’s failure to make any payment due hereunder (subject to Seller’s rights with respect to disputed payments under Section 9.5 and net of outstanding damages and any other rights of offset that Seller may have pursuant to this PPA); (6) Seller’s failure to maintain in effect any agreements required to deliver the Contract Capacity and Contract Energy to the Point of Delivery including, but not limited to, the LGIAs, fuel supply and transportation agreements (to the extent Seller is required to procure and deliver fuel pursuant to the Fuel Supply and Delivery Addendum), and any other required agreements; (7) Seller’s failure to maintain in full force and effect the Air Permit or any other permit required for the operation of the Facility; or (8) Seller’s failure to comply with any other material obligation under this PPA that would result in a material adverse impact on BH/CO Electric. (C) Subject to extension for Force Majeure or delay attributable to BH/CO Electric under Section 14.4, Seller’s failure to achieve the Commercial Operation Date by the Commercial Operation Milestone, as the same may be extended pursuant to paragraph 4.1(B), shall constitute an Event of Default of Seller upon its occurrence but shall be subject to cure within forty-five (45) Days after the date of written notice from BH/CO Electric to Seller and the Facility Lender, if any, as provided for in Section 13.1; provided, however, that Seller shall have an additional forty-five (45) Day period to achieve the Commercial Operation Date, provided that, on or before the expiration of the initial forty-five (45) Day period, an independent engineer, mutually agreed to by the Parties, retained by BH/CO Electric and paid for by Seller, provides a written opinion to BH/CO Electric stating that Seller’s plan for achieving the Commercial Operation Date is reasonably achievable within such additional forty-five (45) Day cure period. This provision would allow for a total cure period of ninety (90) Days if all conditions of this paragraph are met. Damages under paragraph 12.4(A) shall continue accruing until the occurrence of one of the following events: (i) the Commercial Operation Date is achieved, or (ii) this PPA is terminated. (D) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of Seller upon its occurrence but shall be subject to cure within sixty (60) Days after the date of written notice from BH/CO Electric to Seller (and, if applicable, the Facility Lender pursuant to Section 12.2) as provided for in Section 13.1: (1) Seller’s assignment of this PPA, any direct or indirect change of control of Seller, or Seller’s sale or other transfer of all or any material portion of the Facility, in each case except as permitted in accordance with Article 19; (2) Any representation or warranty made by Seller in this PPA shall prove to have been false or misleading in any material respect when made or ceases to remain true during the Term if such cessation would reasonably be expected to result in a material adverse impact on BH/CO Electric; or (3) The filing of an involuntary case in bankruptcy or any proceeding under any other insolvency law against Seller as debtor that could materially impact Seller’s ability to perform its obligations hereunder; provided, however, that Seller does not obtain a stay or dismissal of the filing within the cure period. 12.2 Facility Lender’s Right to Cure Default of Seller. Seller shall provide BH/CO Electric with a notice identifying the Facility Lender and providing appropriate contact information for the Facility Lender. Following receipt of such notice, BH/CO Electric shall provide notice of any Event of Default of Seller to the Facility Lender, and BH/CO Electric will accept a cure to an Event of Default of Seller performed by the Facility Lender, so long as the cure is accomplished within the applicable cure period set forth in this PPA. 12.3 Events of Default of BH/CO Electric. (A) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of BH/CO Electric upon its occurrence and no cure period shall be applicable: (1) BH/CO Electric’s dissolution or liquidation provided that division of BH/CO Electric into multiple entities shall not constitute dissolution or liquidation; (2) BH/CO Electric’s assignment of this PPA or any of its rights hereunder for the benefit of creditors; or (3) BH/CO Electric’s filing of a voluntary petition in bankruptcy or insolvency or for reorganization or arrangement under the bankruptcy laws of the United States or under any insolvency act of any State, or BH/CO Electric voluntarily taking advantage of any such law or act by answer or otherwise. (B) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of BH/CO Electric upon its occurrence but shall be subject to cure within thirty (30) Days (or, if only curable by performance, rather than the payment of money damages, such longer period as may be reasonably required to effect such a cure, provided that Seller commences the cure within such thirty (30) Day period and diligently pursues such cure to conclusion thereafter) after the date of written notice from Seller to BH/CO Electric as provided for in Section 13.1: (1) BH/CO Electric's failure to make any payment due hereunder (subject to BH/CO Electric’s rights with respect to disputed payments under Section 9.5 and net of outstanding damages and any other rights of offset that BH/CO Electric may have pursuant to this PPA); or (2) BH/CO Electric's failure to comply with any other material obligation under this PPA, that would result in a material adverse impact on Seller. (C) Any of the following shall constitute an Event of Default of BH/CO Electric upon its occurrence but shall be subject to cure within sixty (60) Days after the date of written notice from Seller to BH/CO Electric as provided for in Section 13.1: (1) The filing of an involuntary case in bankruptcy or any proceeding under any other insolvency law against BH/CO Electric that could materially impact BH/CO Electric’s ability to perform its obligations hereunder; provided, however, that BH/CO Electric does not obtain a stay or dismissal of the filing within the cure period; (2) BH/CO Electric’s assignment of this PPA, except as permitted in accordance with Article 19; or (3) Any representation or warranty made by BH/CO Electric in this PPA shall prove to have been false or misleading in any material respect when made or ceases to remain true during the Term if such cessation would reasonably be expected to result in a material adverse impact on Seller. 12.4 Damages Prior to Termination. Upon the occurrence of an Event of Default and without regard to whether there is a cure period for such Event of Default, the non-defaulting Party shall have the right to collect damages accruing prior to the termination of this PPA from the defaulting Party as set forth below, and the payment of any such damages accruing prior to the cure of an Event of Default shall constitute a part of the cure. (A) Damages for Failure to Meet the Commercial Operation Milestone. (1) If Seller fails to meet the Commercial Operation Milestone, as the same may have been extended pursuant to Section 4.1(B), subject to extension for Force Majeure or delay attributable to BH/CO Electric under Section 14.4, Seller shall either: (i) pay damages to BH/CO Electric on account of such delay (“Delay Damages”) in the amounts specified below, unless, (ii) Seller gave BH/CO Electric at least six (6) month’s advance written notice that, in the event of a failure to meet the Commercial Operation Milestone, Seller elects to deliver Seller’s Replacement Power, in which event, Seller shall deliver Seller’s Replacement Power or, if it fails to do so, pay all of BH/CO Electric’s Replacement Power Costs.
